Introduction

In this Homework, I will be examining electricity consumption released by EPIAÅ. Electricity consumption, as we have seen during the lectures based on the weather, special days or specific events, such as university entrance exams, religious holidays, etc. After this examination, I will try to find a pattern that the consumption follows and a general trend. We will use this pattern to decompose it from the data, and then I will use AR, MA and their combination to determine the best fitting prediction method. Such predictions based on consumption is important for companies to plan their production schedules or inventories. This will be a primitive version of works that most of firms deal with in real time.

Question 1

To determine possible types of seasonality exhibited by hourly electricity consumption, I will read the data, group it to see various trends and observe the graphs and autocorrelations for different lags. My assumptions are there can be a hourly trend. Which means on 24 hours lagged hours data we can observe similar pattern. I also think when I group the data as days. There can be a daily trend, I am going to group the data as dates and check for the trends. To examine weekly trend, I will check 7 days autocorrelation. I also group the data according to the months and check the monthly trend over the time. Then, I will decompose the series according to my findings and comment on the remaining randomized data and my success of the trend cath.

data_first_2 <- data[1:72,]

Our assumption seems correct, we can see that 24 hours the pattern. The autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation plots will help us to understand the trend better.

acf(data$cons, main= "Hourly Autocorrelation")

pacf(data$cons, main = "Hourly Partial Autocorrelation")

The autocorrelaton plot proves that there is an hourly trend in the data. Because it makes a wave similar to a cosine plot. Also we can see many partial autocorrelatios out of the limits. There is hourly trend.

I will decompose the series hourly with a frequency of 24 hours and examine the remaining error data.

datats<-ts(data$cons,freq=24)

To determine the decomposition method, I will try both additive and multiplicative methods and see the remaining part of the data to determine the stationarity of the random part.

Starting with the multiplicative decomposition:

data_mult<-decompose(datats,type="multiplicative")
random=data_mult$random
plot(data_mult)

Trend data seems to catch, the overall trend. However, there is another seasonality in the trend itself that can be explained by weekly, monthly or yearly trend. We cannot see the seasonality component from here as there are too many points. Letâs give the seasonality a close look.

plot(data_mult$seasonal[1:24], xlab = "Hour", ylab = "Multiplicative of Hour", main = "Seasonal Component of Trend for Multiplicative")

The seasonality tells us that between 15:00 - 20:00 , the consumption is at its maximum, which makes sense the weather is starts to darken and it is the busy hours of the day. And after 20:00, it starts to decrease. Between 3:00 and 7:00 in the morning it is on its lowest level, which makes perfect sense as lots of people is asleep during that hours.

To determine whether the remaining data is randomized, letâs see the KPSS test:

unt_test=ur.kpss(data_mult$random) 
summary(unt_test)
## 
## ####################### 
## # KPSS Unit Root Test # 
## ####################### 
## 
## Test is of type: mu with 18 lags. 
## 
## Value of test-statistic is: 0.5202 
## 
## Critical value for a significance level of: 
##                 10pct  5pct 2.5pct  1pct
## critical values 0.347 0.463  0.574 0.739

The level is between 5 percent and 2.5 percent. The stationary depends on our confidence interval. For 1 percent, we fail reject the data is stationary, however for 10 we reject. Actually it is normal the data does not take into consideration for example the weekly trend.

Letâs check additive model and compare those.

To see the model evaluation, I am using the function from the lecture hours.

accu=function(actual,forecast){
  n=length(actual)
  error=actual-forecast
  mean=mean(actual)
  sd=sd(actual)
  CV=sd/mean
  FBias=sum(error)/sum(actual)
  MAPE=sum(abs(error/actual))/n
  RMSE=sqrt(sum(error^2)/n)
  MAD=sum(abs(error))/n
  MADP=sum(abs(error))/sum(abs(actual))
  WMAPE=MAD/mean
  l=data.frame(n,mean,sd,CV,FBias,MAPE,RMSE,MAD,MADP,WMAPE)
  return(l)
}

The function will give me my error metrics.

accu(daily_actual_last$mean_consumption_actual, daily_actual_last$daily_prediction)

Conclusion

In this HW3, first of all I have examined the possible seasonalities that electricity consumption data may have. My data shows hourly, weekly, monthly seasonality. I have explained the possible reasons for this kind of trends. Such as closed workplaces during Sundays for weekly trend, air conditioning during summer for monthly trend. Special days limits my time series analysis, as they create outliers and damage my models accuracy. For the next part, I have examined 168 hour data, create AR, MA and ARIMA models. The model was the lowest AIC value is ARIMA(10,0,12). I have used that model in my predictions and obtained a prediction that performed acceptably in the forecast.
